</p><p>Superscript 0 indicates ion concentrations in the physiological resting state. Unless otherwise stated <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1003941.e026.jpg"/></inline-formula> and <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1003941.e027.jpg"/></inline-formula> are used as initial conditions in the simulations. Constrained ion concentrations (<xref ref-type="disp-formula" rid="pcbi.1003941.e020">Eqs. (7)</xref>&#x02013;(<xref ref-type="disp-formula" rid="pcbi.1003941.e023">10)</xref>) then also take their physiological resting state values. These ion concentrations, the membrane capacitance <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1003941.e028.jpg"/></inline-formula>, the gating time scale parameter <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1003941.e029.jpg"/></inline-formula>, the conversion factor <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1003941.e030.jpg"/></inline-formula> from currents to ion fluxes, and the ICS and ECS volumes <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1003941.e031.jpg"/></inline-formula> are listed in <xref ref-type="table" rid="pcbi-1003941-t001">Tab. 1</xref>. The conversion factor <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1003941.e032.jpg"/></inline-formula> is an expression of the membrane surface area <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1003941.e033.jpg"/></inline-formula> and Faraday's constant <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1003941.e034.jpg"/></inline-formula> (both given in <xref ref-type="table" rid="pcbi-1003941-t001">Tab. 1</xref>, too): <disp-formula id="pcbi.1003941.e035"><graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1003941.e035.jpg" position="anchor" orientation="portrait"/><label>(13)</label></disp-formula>We remark that all parameters in <xref ref-type="table" rid="pcbi-1003941-t001">Tab. 1</xref> are given in typical units of the respective quantities. The numerical values in these units can directly be used for simulations. Time is then given in msec, the